# Section 1 - Domain Understanding 
# Diabetes is a severe disease with no cure and there have been many risk factors that have been identified for diabetes: 
# "ethnicity, family history of diabetes, age, excess weight, unhealthy diet, physical inactivity, and smoking" (Chang et al., 2022). 
# Diabetes can lead to further health complications, including kidney disease and even death. Thus, the need for developing a 
# prediction agent/machine learning solution that can handle the complexity of a disease like diabetes is evident. 
# # For example, the earlier diabetes is caught and managed well, the better a patient is set up for success to live with a chronic illness. 

# The Pima Indians Diabetes dataset comprises of Pima Indian females aged 21 years or older as there has been a high rate of 
# diabetes seen amongst this Native American group located in Mexico and Arizona. This dataset has been experimented with to
# developing a machine learning algorithm to predict a persons likelihood of developing diabetes based on risk factors. Each 
# row in the data corresponds to one individual Pima Indian female. Each row contains information on the number of pregnancies this 
# individual female has had, glucose level, blood pressure level, skin thickness, insulin level, BMI, "DiabetesPedigreeFunction" 
# which "calculates diabetes likelihood depending on the subject's age and his/her diabetic family history" (Das, et al., 2022), age, and 
# binary indicator, "Outcome" which corresponds to the model's indicator of diabetic or not. 

# This dataset has many purposes, but in this context, it can be used to answer several questions regarding the risk factors associated 
# with diabetes. For example, one could potentially answer the question "by what magnitude does being from an indigienous group 
# increase the likelihood of being a diabetic" or "by what magnitude does being a woman increase the likelihood of being a diabetic?". 
# Taking this one step further, we may be able to answer a question such as "does having one or more pregnancies increase the risk 
# of developing diabetes"? 

# Citations: 
# Chang, V., Bailey, J., Xu, Q. A., & Sun, Z. (2022). Pima Indians diabetes mellitus classification based on machine learning (ML) 
# algorithms. Neural computing & applications, 1-17. Advance online publication. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00521-022-07049-z. 

# Das, M., Bhattacharyya, G., Gong, R. (2022). Determinants of gestational diabetes pedigree function for pima Indian females. 
# Intern Med Open J. 2022; 6(1): 9-13. https://doi.org/10.17140/IMOJ-6-121.

# Section: 2.1 - Describe the meaning and type of data for each feature. 

# Before converting each attribute to be of numeric type, each attribues values have a type of "object". 
pima["Pregnancies"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["Pregnancies"], errors = 'coerce')
pima["Glucose"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["Glucose"], errors = 'coerce')
pima["BloodPressure"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["BloodPressure"], errors = 'coerce')
pima["SkinThickness"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["SkinThickness"], errors = 'coerce')
pima["Insulin"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["Insulin"], errors = 'coerce')
pima["BMI"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["BMI"], errors = 'coerce')
pima["DiabetesPedigreeFunction"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["DiabetesPedigreeFunction"], errors = 'coerce')
pima["Age"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["Age"], errors = 'coerce')
pima["Outcome"] = pd.to_numeric(pima["Outcome"], errors = 'coerce')

# After converting, each attributes collection of data objects has a type of float64. 

# 'Pregnancies' indicates the number of times an individual has been pregnant. 

# 'Glucose'indicates the "plasma glucose concentration at 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test (GTIT)". 

# 'BloodPressure' indicates the "diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)". 

# 'SkinThickness' indicates the "triceps skin fold thickness (mm)". 

# 'Insulin' indicates the "2-hour Serum insulin" (µh/ml)".

# 'BMI' indicates the "Body mass index [weight in kg/(Height in m)]". 

# 'DiabetesPedigreeFunction' indicates the "Diabetes pedigree function". 

# 'Age' indicates the individuals age in years. 

# 'Outcome' is an  binary factor variable where the values (i.e. 0 or 1), indicate "non-diabetic/diabetic". 

# All attributes are ratio attributes, other than Outcome which is a nominal attribute. 

# Citation: 
# Chang, V., Bailey, J., Xu, Q. A., & Sun, Z. (2022). Pima Indians diabetes mellitus classification based on machine learning (ML) 
# algorithms. Neural computing & applications, 1-17. Advance online publication. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00521-022-07049-z.

# Now, we have successfully dealt with outliers. However, we are not done. 

# SkinThickness cannot be 0.0mm as this is humanly impossible. Furthermore, Insulin cannot be 0.0 µh/ml. 
# We will consider 0.0mm and 0.0 µh/ml to be missing data, and will replace those 0.0 values with the 
# mean of SkinThickness and Insulin, respectively. 

mean_outcome1 = pima2[pima2["Outcome"] == 1]["SkinThickness"].mean()
mean_outcome0 = pima2[pima2["Outcome"] == 0]["SkinThickness"].mean()
pima2.loc[(pima2["Outcome"] == 1) & (pima2["SkinThickness"] == 0), "SkinThickness"] = mean_outcome1
pima2.loc[(pima2["Outcome"] == 0) & (pima2["SkinThickness"] == 0), "SkinThickness"] = mean_outcome0

# Section 3.2 - Did you decide to implement any feature transformations? If so, why? 
pima2.describe()
# All of our attributes have different units. Let's normalize all of the ratio attributes using z-score 
# normalization. By doing so and scaling all of our attributes to a common range, our attributes will be 
# more comparable and this will likely help our model. 
outcome = "Outcome"
pima3 = pima2.copy()
update = [col for col in pima3.columns if col != outcome]
for col in update: 
    mean = pima3[col].mean()
    std = pima3[col].std()
    pima3[col] = (pima3[col] - mean)/std
In [1175]:
# Section 3.3 - Did you decide to create any new features? If so, why? 
# I decided to add a feature "MultiplePregnancies" to indicate if an individual has had more than 1.0 
# pregnancies. "In analyses stratified by age and region, women with two, three, or four or more children 
# were at 17%, 30% and 45% increased risk of diabetes compared with women with one child (p < 0.0001 for trend)" 
# (Peters et al., 2016). If an individual has had more than 1 pregnancy, I assigned a value of 1. If an individual 
# has had 0.0 or 1.0 pregnancies, I assigned a value of 0. 

# Furthermore, "Type 2 diabetes is at an epidemic level among American Indians who have the highest prevalence of
# diabetes in any group". Why? "While a multitude of factors contribute to the high incidence of type 2 diabetes for 
# Natives, the alarming statistics can be traced back to the change from pre-reservation traditional diets and 
# lifestyles to more westernized sedentary lifestyles and foods. For example, many Native people went from active 
# hunting and gathering to post-reservation diets with a troubling amount of refined white four and fat, which 
# leads to today's diabetes crisis" ("Type 2 Diabetes in Native Communities", n.d.). Because of this, I decided to 
# create another feature, "Overweight" where 1 is assigned to an individual if their BMI is over 25.0. 

# I make these features in section 3.5. 

# Citation: 
# Peters, S.A., Yang, L., Guo, Y., Chen, Y., Bian, Z., Millwood, I., Bragg, F., Zhou, X., Ge, P., Chen, B., Gao, Y., 
# Li, Y., Chen, J., Li, L., Woodward, M., Chen, Z., & China Kadoorie Biobank Collaboration Group (2016). 
# Parenthood and the risk of diabetes in men and women: a 7 year prospective study of 0.5 million individuals. 
# Diabetologia, 59(8), 1675-1682. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00125-016-3980-x. 

# "Type 2 Diabetes in Native Communities" (n.d.). First Nations Development Institute. 
# https://www.firstnations.org/wp-content/uploads/publication-attachments/5%20Fact%20Sheet%20Type%202%20Diabetes%20In%20Native%20Communities%20FNDI.pdf

# Assuming you use a cutoff of 0.5 when classifying diabetes, what is your misclassification table? 
predicted_probs = my_model_full.predict()
predicted_probs

def table(predicted_probs, labels, cutoff):
    """ Replacement for R's table funcion. """
    predicted_outcome = (predicted_probs > cutoff).astype(int)
    df = pd.DataFrame({"predicted_outcome": predicted_outcome, "actual_outcome": labels})
    return pd.crosstab(index=df["actual_outcome"], columns=df["predicted_outcome"], margins=False)

table(predicted_probs, pima2["Outcome"], cutoff=0.5)
# With a cutoff of 0.5, the model accurately classified 431 individuals as non-diabetic and 158 individuals as 
# diabetic. 69 individuals were falsely predicted as diabetic by the model, and 110 individuals were falsely 
# predicted as non-diabetic by the model.

# The odds ratio for "BMI" is 1.61.
# The odds ratio for "DiabetesPedigreeFunction" is 1.40. 
# The odds ratio for "Age" is 1.72. 

# Interpretation: 

# Holding all other predictors constant, for a one unit increase in Glucose, the odds of Outcome being 1 
# increases by a factor of 2.83. 

# Holding all other predictors constant, for a one unit increase in BMI, the odds of Outcome being 1 
# increases by a factor of 1.61. 

# Holding all other predictors constant, for a one unit increase in the DiabetesPedigreeFunction, the odds 
# of Outcome being 1 increases by a factor of 1.40.

# Holding all other predictors constant, for a one year increase in Age, the odds of Outcome being 1 
# increases by a factor of 1.72.

# and "Overweight" as parameters to the model, but only very slightly, leading to the conclusion that adding in 
# "MultiplePregnancies" and "Overweight" is not particularly useful.

# Section: 4 - Conclusions 

# Overall, in theory, this dataset is interesting to use for a model that predicts diabetes as American 
# Indians are a group that are effected by the prevalence of diabetes as I explained. However, the dataset 
# itself comes with flaws. For example, "Insulin" contains a lot of 0.00 µh/ml values. It is hard to say whether 
# these values should be interpreted as missing values, or if these are values indicating that ones pancreas 
# is in fact not producing enough insulin. 

# Through model exploration, I learned that "Glucose", "BMI", "DiabetesPedigreeFunction", and "Age" are the most 
# useful predictors in prediciting diabetes for this data set. However, there is a signficant number of individuals 
# that are falsely classified as diabetic or non-diabetic when they should not have been. 

# Furthermore, in section 2, we saw that there are not significant relationships amongst any of the pairs 
# of attributes. While in some sense this is good as we do not want covariates to be linearly dependent on one 
# another necessarily, it also makes it so that these predictors may not be necessarily efficient in 
# predicting diabetes for this dataset. Many of the predictors are not correlated with one another and therefore, the model 
# may miss relationships between the predictors that could be important for predicting a response. In other words, 
# the predictors being so uncorrelated could indicate that these are not the best predictors for predicitng 
# diabetes for this dataset. 

# Additional data may make the model more helpful. If I had more time, I would investigate what doctors and
# diabetes researchers say are the best indicators of diabetes, and I would collect data on those indicators, 
# and try to create a better model.
